  "diary": "Woke up to that perfect early-June light—coffee tasted better somehow. Got through the morning tax grind at the office without too much pain, then couldn't resist ducking out for the USA-Wales match. Pike Place was buzzing with people and the energy was electric. Grabbed a beer and some fish and chips, watched the whole thing with strangers who became temporary friends. The sun was still high when I walked back downtown, and honestly the whole detour felt worth it. Back at the office for a few more hours of spreadsheets, then home to Madrona. Made a simple dinner and spent the evening at the pottery wheel—my hands needed that. There's something about centering clay that makes the day settle.",
  "thought_process": "I almost skipped the game, honestly. Tax season has me in a tunnel-vision headspace, but the weather was too good and something about a World Cup Monday felt rare. The Light Rail closure actually worked in my favor—forced me to walk, which meant I ended up at Pike Place anyway. Those couple hours away from the desk recharged me more than I expected. By evening, I needed the pottery studio to decompress; accounts and percentages had my brain fried. I chose leisure over anything ambitious because I knew my body was asking for it. The day had this unexpected rhythm—work, then play, then work again, then creation. Sometimes you need that pattern to feel whole.",
